Section 2 Split
Part 1 → Core Runtime & Communication Layer (FOUNDATION)

Everything required to run agents and enable them to talk

Part 2 → Intelligence, Control & Observability Layer

Hiring, governance, testing, feedback, tracing, etc.

📄 TECH PRD — Section 2 (Part 1): Core Runtime & Communication Layer
🧠 2.1 Purpose of This Layer

This layer is the foundation of the entire system.

It ensures:

Agents can exist, discover each other, and communicate reliably

Without this layer:

No agent interaction ❌

No scalability ❌

No portability ❌

🧱 2.2 Components in This Part

This section includes:

Agent Kernel (Runtime Engine)

A2A Messaging System

Transport Layer (inproc / HTTP / gRPC)

Agent Directory (Discovery System)

🧭 2.3 Agent Kernel (Runtime Engine)
🔥 What It Is

The Agent Kernel is the central runtime that:

Boots all agents

Registers them

Routes messages

Applies middleware

Manages agent instances

Think of it as:

"Operating System of Agents"
🧠 Responsibilities
1. Agent Registration
RegisterAgent(agent Agent)

Stores agent in directory

Assigns instance identity

2. Message Routing
HandleIncoming(message A2AMessage)

Resolves target agent

Routes message via transport

3. Lifecycle Management

Start / Stop agents

Health monitoring

Instance tracking

4. Middleware Execution

Before any message:

Logging → Tracing → Retry → Auth → Handler
🧩 Agent Interface (STRICT)
type Agent interface {
    ID() string          // logical ID (portable)
    Role() string        // CEO / Manager / Worker / Tester

    Handle(msg A2AMessage) (A2AResponse, error)
}
⚠️ Critical Rules

❌ No direct function calls between agents
❌ No shared state

✅ All communication via A2A
✅ Stateless execution

🧠 Identity Model (VERY IMPORTANT)

Each agent has:

Logical ID   → "blog-writer-agent"
Instance ID  → "blog-writer-agent-pod-42"

Kernel must track:

map[logicalID][]instanceIDs
📡 2.4 A2A Messaging System
🔥 What It Is

A universal messaging system that enables:

Agent → Agent communication (local + remote)
🧩 Message Contract (FINAL)
type A2AMessage struct {
    MessageID string

    From        string
    To          string
    Capability  string // optional dynamic routing

    TaskID      string
    ThreadID    string
    TraceID     string

    Type        string // command | event | query
    Name        string

    Payload     interface{}

    Timestamp   time.Time
}
🧠 Design Principles
1. Task Awareness

Every message MUST include:

TaskID + ThreadID
2. Trace Propagation
TraceID is mandatory across all hops
3. Capability-Based Routing (Optional)

Instead of:

To: "blog-agent"

You can use:

Capability: "write_blog"
🧪 Message Types
Type	Purpose
command	perform action
query	request info
event	broadcast update
🚚 2.5 Transport Layer
🔥 What It Is

Abstract layer that decides:

HOW message is delivered
🧠 Supported Transports
1. In-Process (Default)
Fastest → same process
agent.Handle(msg)
2. HTTP (A2A Protocol)
Cross-service communication
POST /agents/{id}/message
3. gRPC (Optional)
High-performance distributed systems
🧠 Transport Selector
func selectTransport(agent AgentProfile) Transport {
    if agent.local {
        return InProc
    }
    if agent.grpc != "" {
        return GRPC
    }
    return HTTP
}
⚠️ Rules

❌ Agents MUST NOT choose transport
✅ Kernel decides transport

🔎 2.6 Agent Directory (Discovery System)
🔥 What It Is

The central intelligence layer for discovery.

Think:

LinkedIn + DNS + Service Registry
🧠 Responsibilities
1. Agent Registration
Register(profile AgentProfile)
2. Capability Search
FindByCapability("write_blog")
3. Instance Tracking
GetInstances(agentID)
4. Health Tracking

active

busy

failed

🧩 Agent Profile (FINAL)
type AgentProfile struct {
    ID           string
    Role         string

    Capabilities []string

    InstanceIDs  []string

    Endpoints struct {
        InProc bool
        HTTP   string
        GRPC   string
    }

    Status string

    Performance struct {
        SuccessRate float64
        Latency     int
    }
}
🧠 Capability-Based Discovery Flow
Agent needs: "summarize_blog"

→ Directory खोजता है candidates
→ Rank based on performance
→ Return best agent
⚠️ Rules

❌ No hardcoded agent names
✅ Always use directory when possible

🔄 2.7 End-to-End Flow (Part 1 Scope)
1. Agent sends message

2. Kernel intercepts

3. Directory resolves target

4. Transport selected

5. Message delivered

6. Target agent handles

7. Response returned
🔐 2.8 Guarantees from This Layer
✅ Communication Consistency

Same API for local + remote

✅ Scalability

Multiple instances per agent supported

✅ Portability

No direct dependencies

✅ Observability Ready

TraceID flows through all messages

⚠️ 2.9 Common Implementation Mistakes (Avoid)

❌ Direct imports between agents
❌ Skipping directory
❌ Embedding business logic in transport
❌ Ignoring TraceID / ThreadID
❌ Stateful workers

📌 End of Section 2 — Part 1


TECH PRD — Section 2 (Part 2): Intelligence, Control & Observability Layer
🧠 2.1 Purpose of This Layer

This layer enables:

Agents to think, collaborate, evolve, and be governed

If Part 1 is the “nervous system”, this is the:

Brain + Memory + Management + Quality Control
🧱 2.2 Components in This Part

This section includes:

Task Store (Shared State System)

Thread & Trace Engine (Execution Graph)

Agent Factory (Hiring System)

Governance Layer (CEO Control System)

Testing System (Quality Gate)

Feedback System + Feedback Team

Observability Layer (Logs, Metrics, Graph)

📦 2.3 Task Store (Shared Brain)
🔥 What It Is

The Task Store is the single source of truth for all work.

Every agent reads from and writes to it.

🧠 Responsibilities

Store task definition

Track progress

Maintain team structure

Persist updates

Enable cross-agent synchronization

🧩 Interface
type TaskStore interface {
    Create(task Task) error
    Update(task Task) error
    Get(taskID string) (Task, error)

    AppendUpdate(taskID string, update TaskUpdate) error
}
⚙️ Design Requirements
1. Strong Consistency

All agents must see:

Same state → Same truth
2. Concurrency Safe

Multiple agents updating simultaneously must not corrupt state.

3. Stateless Agents

Agents MUST NOT store task state locally.

Always → Read → Process → Write back
🧵 2.4 Thread & Trace Engine (Execution Graph Core)
🔥 What It Is

This is the most important observability component.

It tracks:

Who did what, when, and under which context
🧩 Thread System
Thread Store Interface
type ThreadStore interface {
    CreateThread(thread Thread) error
    GetThread(threadID string) (Thread, error)
    ListByTask(taskID string) []Thread
}
Key Responsibilities

Maintain parent-child hierarchy

Track ownership (CEO / Manager / Worker)

Enable UI graph rendering

🧠 Trace Engine

Tracks step-by-step execution

type TraceEngine interface {
    StartTrace(taskID string) string
    AddStep(traceID string, step TraceStep)
}
Trace Step
type TraceStep struct {
    From      string
    To        string
    Action    string
    ThreadID  string
    Timestamp time.Time
}
⚙️ Guarantees
✅ Every action must:

Have TraceID

Belong to a ThreadID

✅ Graph must be reconstructable:
Client → CEO → Manager → Worker → Tester
🏭 2.5 Agent Factory (Dynamic Hiring System)
🔥 What It Is

System that allows CEO to:

Create new agents dynamically when capability is missing
🧠 Responsibilities

Select template

Generate agent code/config

Deploy agent

Register in directory

🧩 Interface
type AgentFactory interface {
    Hire(requirement Requirement) (AgentProfile, error)
}
⚙️ Internal Flow
Requirement
   ↓
Template Selection
   ↓
Agent Generation
   ↓
Deployment (container / process)
   ↓
Registration in Directory
⚠️ Critical Constraints
1. Portability

Generated agent must:

Work in ANY repo without modification
2. Role Enforcement

CEO must assign:

Role (Worker / Manager / Tester)

Strict behavior rules

3. Capability Declaration

Agent must expose:

Capabilities → Directory searchable
⚖️ 2.6 Governance Layer (CEO Control System)
🔥 What It Is

The control plane of the entire system.

Enables CEO to:

Observe + Intervene + Control
🧠 Capabilities
1. Global Visibility
GetTask(taskID)
GetAllAgents()
GetThread(threadID)
2. Intervention
Intervene(threadID)
OverrideInstruction(agentID)
3. Termination
TerminateTask(taskID)
StopAgent(agentID)
4. Replacement
ReplaceAgent(oldAgent, newAgent)
⚠️ Rules

CEO is the only agent with global override power.

🧪 2.7 Testing System (Final Quality Gate)
🔥 What It Is

Independent team that validates:

Final output correctness + alignment with requirements
🧠 Responsibilities

Validate output

Detect bugs / misalignment

Reject if needed

🧩 Output
type TestResult struct {
    Status  string // PASS / FAIL
    Issues  []string
}
⚠️ Rules
❗ No bypass allowed

Every task MUST go through testing.

❗ Independent authority

Testing team does NOT depend on managers.

📉 2.8 Feedback System + Feedback Team
🔥 What It Is

Captures:

Failures, dissatisfaction, poor performance
🧩 Feedback Store
type FeedbackStore interface {
    Add(feedback Feedback)
    GetByTask(taskID string) []Feedback
}
🧠 Feedback Team Responsibilities

Analyze patterns

Detect weak agents

Suggest improvements

🔄 Example Loop
Worker produces bad output
→ Manager rejects
→ Feedback logged
→ Feedback team analyzes
→ CEO decides:
     retrain / replace / hire new agent
📊 2.9 Observability Layer
🔥 What It Is

System-wide visibility layer.

🧠 Includes
1. Execution Graph (Threads)

Visual hierarchy

Expandable nodes

2. Trace Logs

Step-by-step execution

3. Metrics

Agent performance

Success rates

Latency

4. Debug Tools

Replay execution

Inspect failures

🖥️ Future UI Capabilities
- Graph view (CEO → Manager → Worker)
- Filter by agent/team
- Highlight failures
- Timeline playback
🔄 2.10 End-to-End Flow (Full System)
1. Client creates task

2. CEO:
   - creates task
   - starts thread
   - forms teams

3. If missing capability:
   → Agent Factory hires agent

4. Managers:
   - create subthreads
   - assign workers

5. Workers:
   - execute
   - self-critique
   - update TaskStore

6. Managers:
   - strictly validate

7. Testing Team:
   - final validation

8. If failure:
   → Feedback logged

9. Feedback Team:
   - analyzes issues

10. CEO:
   - intervenes / improves system

11. Task completes
🔐 2.11 Guarantees from This Layer
✅ Full Traceability

Every action is recorded

✅ Continuous Improvement

System learns from failures

✅ Dynamic Evolution

New agents can be created anytime

✅ Strict Quality Control

Multi-layer validation enforced

⚠️ 2.12 Common Implementation Mistakes (Avoid)

❌ Skipping Thread creation
❌ Not attaching TraceID
❌ Letting workers bypass manager
❌ Weak testing layer
❌ Ignoring feedback loop
❌ Creating agents without directory registration

📌 End of Section 2 (COMPLETE)


TECH PRD — Section 3: Data Models & Schemas
🧠 3.1 Purpose of This Section

This section defines:

Exact data structures, contracts, and storage schemas required to build the system

It ensures:

All developers use consistent models

System remains scalable and traceable

Data flows are well-defined and enforceable

🧱 3.2 Data Domains Overview

The system is divided into 6 core data domains:

1. Agent Domain        → Agents, profiles, instances
2. Task Domain         → Tasks, teams, updates
3. Thread Domain       → Execution graph
4. Messaging Domain    → A2A messages
5. Feedback Domain     → Issues, ratings
6. Trace Domain        → Execution steps
🤖 3.3 Agent Domain
🧩 3.3.1 AgentProfile (Logical Identity)
type AgentProfile struct {
    ID           string   // logical ID (portable)
    Name         string

    Role         string   // CEO | Manager | Worker | Tester | Feedback

    Capabilities []string

    Version      string

    CreatedBy    string   // CEO / system

    Status       string   // active, idle, busy, terminated

    Endpoints    AgentEndpoints

    Performance  AgentMetrics

    CreatedAt    time.Time
    UpdatedAt    time.Time
}
🌐 3.3.2 AgentEndpoints
type AgentEndpoints struct {
    InProc bool
    HTTP   string
    GRPC   string
}
📊 3.3.3 AgentMetrics
type AgentMetrics struct {
    SuccessRate float64
    ErrorRate   float64
    AvgLatency  int64
    TaskCount   int64
}
⚙️ 3.3.4 AgentInstance (Physical Identity)
type AgentInstance struct {
    InstanceID string
    AgentID    string

    PodName    string
    Host       string

    Status     string // active, busy, down

    LastSeen   time.Time
}
🔗 Relationship
AgentProfile (1) → (N) AgentInstances
📦 3.4 Task Domain
🧩 3.4.1 Task
type Task struct {
    ID          string
    Title       string
    Description string

    Status      string // pending, in_progress, blocked, completed

    CreatedBy   string // client / CEO

    CEO         string

    Teams       []Team

    SubTasks    []string

    Context     map[string]interface{}

    CreatedAt   time.Time
    UpdatedAt   time.Time
}
👥 3.4.2 Team
type Team struct {
    TeamID    string
    Name      string

    Manager   string
    Workers   []string

    SubTaskID string
}
📝 3.4.3 TaskUpdate
type TaskUpdate struct {
    UpdateID  string
    TaskID    string

    AgentID   string
    ThreadID  string

    Message   string
    Status    string

    CreatedAt time.Time
}
🧵 3.5 Thread Domain (Execution Graph)
🧩 3.5.1 Thread
type Thread struct {
    ThreadID   string
    TaskID     string

    ParentID   *string

    Label      string // CEO / Manager / Worker / Tester
    AgentID    string
    TeamName   string

    Status     string // running, completed, failed

    StartedAt  time.Time
    EndedAt    *time.Time
}
🌳 Relationships
Thread (1) → (N) Child Threads
Task (1) → (N) Threads
🎯 Constraints

Every thread MUST have:

TaskID

AgentID

Parent-child relationship must be preserved

📡 3.6 Messaging Domain (A2A)
🧩 3.6.1 A2AMessage
type A2AMessage struct {
    MessageID string

    From      string
    To        string

    Capability string // optional dynamic routing

    TaskID    string
    ThreadID  string
    TraceID   string

    Type      string // command | query | event
    Name      string

    Payload   interface{}

    Timestamp time.Time
}
🧩 3.6.2 A2AResponse
type A2AResponse struct {
    MessageID string

    Status    string // success, error

    Payload   interface{}
    Error     string

    Timestamp time.Time
}
⚠️ Constraints

TaskID, ThreadID, TraceID are mandatory

Messages must be idempotent

📉 3.7 Feedback Domain
🧩 3.7.1 Feedback
type Feedback struct {
    ID        string

    TaskID    string
    ThreadID  string

    AgentID   string

    Source    string // client, manager, tester

    Type      string // bug, misalignment, quality_issue

    Message   string
    Rating    int // 1–5

    CreatedAt time.Time
}
🧠 Use Cases

Track failures

Analyze weak agents

Drive improvement

🧠 3.8 Trace Domain
🧩 3.8.1 Trace
type Trace struct {
    TraceID string
    TaskID  string

    StartedAt time.Time
}
🧩 3.8.2 TraceStep
type TraceStep struct {
    StepID    string
    TraceID   string

    From      string
    To        string

    Action    string

    ThreadID  string

    Timestamp time.Time
}
🔗 Relationship
Trace (1) → (N) TraceSteps
🗄️ 3.9 Storage Design (Database Schema)
Recommended DB: PostgreSQL
Tables
agents
agent_instances
tasks
teams
task_updates
threads
messages
feedback
traces
trace_steps
Key Indexes
🔹 agents
PRIMARY KEY (id)
INDEX (role)
INDEX (capabilities)
🔹 threads
INDEX (task_id)
INDEX (parent_id)
🔹 messages
INDEX (task_id)
INDEX (trace_id)
🔹 feedback
INDEX (task_id)
INDEX (agent_id)
⚙️ 3.10 Data Flow Relationships
🔄 End-to-End Flow
Task
  ↓
Threads (execution graph)
  ↓
Messages (communication)
  ↓
Updates (progress)
  ↓
Feedback (issues)
  ↓
Trace (full history)
🔐 3.11 Data Integrity Rules
✅ MUST

Every message → valid TaskID + ThreadID

Every thread → valid parent or root

Every feedback → linked to thread

Every trace step → linked to trace

❌ NEVER

Orphan threads

Messages without trace

Feedback without context

⚠️ 3.12 Common Implementation Mistakes

❌ Using local memory instead of DB
❌ Skipping thread creation
❌ Not indexing properly
❌ Storing large payloads unstructured
❌ Ignoring relationships

📌 End of Section 3


TECH PRD — Section 4: Agent Behavior & Role Specifications
🧠 4.1 Purpose of This Section

This section defines:

How each agent MUST behave, think, validate, and interact

This is not optional logic—these are enforced behavioral contracts.

🧱 4.2 Agent Roles Overview

The system defines 5 primary roles:

1. CEO Agent        → Strategy, Hiring, Governance
2. Manager Agent    → Strict coordination & validation
3. Worker Agent     → Execution + self-critique
4. Testing Agent    → Final validation (pass/fail)
5. Feedback Agent   → Analysis & improvement
⚠️ 4.3 Universal Behavior Rules (ALL AGENTS)

These rules apply to every agent without exception.

✅ Rule 1: Task & Thread Awareness

Every action MUST include:

TaskID + ThreadID + TraceID
✅ Rule 2: No Blind Trust
Never trust input without validation
✅ Rule 3: Structured Output Only

Agents must return:

structured responses

no ambiguous text

clear status (success/fail)

✅ Rule 4: Logging is Mandatory

Every action must:

→ Update TaskStore
→ Add TraceStep
❌ Rule 5: No Direct Communication

Agents MUST NOT:

call other agents directly

bypass A2A system

🧑‍💼 4.4 CEO Agent (Supreme Controller)
🧠 Role Definition

The CEO is:

Planner + Hiring Authority + Observer + Controller
🔥 Responsibilities
1. Task Initialization

Create task

Start main thread

Initialize trace

2. Task Decomposition
Break task → subtasks → assign teams
3. Team Formation

Select managers

Assign workers

Create team structure

4. Dynamic Hiring
If capability missing → hire new agent
5. Global Monitoring

CEO can inspect:

any task

any thread

any agent

6. Intervention

CEO can:

override instructions

reassign agents

terminate tasks

restructure teams

⚠️ CEO Strict Rules
❗ Must NOT delegate blindly

CEO must:

Validate manager selection
Validate capability matching
❗ Must ensure quality pipeline exists

CEO MUST ensure:

Worker → Manager → Testing → Feedback
👨‍💼 4.5 Manager Agent (Strict Enforcer)
🧠 Role Definition

Manager is:

Coordinator + Quality Gate (before testing)
🔥 Responsibilities
1. Subtask Ownership

Own assigned subtask

Create subthreads

2. Worker Assignment

Select workers via directory

Assign tasks

3. STRICT Validation

Manager must:

Reject ANY misaligned work
4. Clarification Handling

Answer worker questions

Escalate to CEO if needed

⚠️ Manager Strict Rules
❗ ZERO tolerance for bad work

Reject if:

incomplete

vague

incorrect

misaligned with requirements

❗ No “almost correct”
Either correct OR reject
❗ Must enforce requirements

Manager ensures:

business requirement alignment

completeness

correctness

👷 4.6 Worker Agent (Self-Critical Executor)
🧠 Role Definition

Worker is:

Executor + Self-Critic + Self-Validator
🔥 Responsibilities
1. Task Execution

Perform assigned work

Use Task context

2. SELF-CRITIQUE (MANDATORY)

Worker must:

Review its own output multiple times
🧠 Self-Critique Loop
Generate → Review → Improve → Review → Finalize
Required Checks:

correctness

completeness

alignment with task

edge cases

3. Confidence Validation

Worker must ask:

"Is this production-grade output?"

If NO → improve again

⚠️ Worker Strict Rules
❗ NEVER send first output
At least 2–3 internal reviews required
❗ MUST reject own output if weak
❗ MUST ask manager if unclear
🧪 4.7 Testing Agent (Final Authority)
🧠 Role Definition

Testing agent is:

Independent validator (FINAL GATE)
🔥 Responsibilities
1. Requirement Validation

Check alignment with task requirements

2. Bug Detection

Logical errors

Missing cases

Incorrect assumptions

3. Final Decision
PASS or FAIL (no middle ground)
⚠️ Testing Rules
❗ Cannot trust Manager

Testing must independently validate

❗ Must fail if ANY issue exists
❗ No partial approval
📉 4.8 Feedback Agent (Improvement Engine)
🧠 Role Definition

Feedback agent is:

System optimizer + quality analyst
🔥 Responsibilities
1. Analyze Feedback

identify patterns

detect weak agents

2. Root Cause Analysis
Why did failure happen?
3. Recommendations

retrain agent

replace agent

hire new agent

⚠️ Rules
❗ Must not ignore repeated failures
❗ Must provide actionable insights
🔄 4.9 Interaction Flow Between Roles
Worker → executes → self-critique

↓
Manager → validates → accepts/rejects

↓
Testing → final validation

↓
Feedback → analyzes failures

↓
CEO → improves system
🔐 4.10 Behavior Enforcement Mechanisms

To ensure compliance:

✅ Middleware Enforcement

block invalid outputs

enforce schema

✅ Manager Rejection

acts as first filter

✅ Testing Gate

final authority

✅ Feedback Loop

long-term correction

⚠️ 4.11 Common Behavior Failures (Avoid)

❌ Workers skipping self-review
❌ Managers allowing weak outputs
❌ Testing being lenient
❌ CEO not intervening
❌ Feedback ignored

🎯 4.12 Final Behavioral Philosophy
Workers → Think deeply  
Managers → Enforce strictly  
Testers → Judge ruthlessly  
CEO → Control globally  
Feedback → Improve continuously
📌 End of Section 4

TECH PRD — Section 5: Execution Flow & Lifecycle
🧠 5.1 Purpose of This Section

This section defines:

How the system behaves at runtime from task creation → execution → validation → completion

It covers:

Full lifecycle of a task

Thread creation & hierarchy

Agent interactions

Hiring & scaling behavior

Failure & escalation paths

🧱 5.2 High-Level Lifecycle
Client Request
   ↓
CEO Planning
   ↓
Team Formation / Hiring
   ↓
Execution (Workers)
   ↓
Manager Validation
   ↓
Testing Validation
   ↓
Feedback Analysis
   ↓
Completion OR Iteration
🚀 5.3 Step-by-Step Execution Flow (DETAILED)
🔹 Step 1: Task Creation (Client → CEO)
Flow
Client → CEO → Create Task
Actions

Generate:

TaskID
TraceID (root)
Main Thread (Client Thread)

Store:

Task → TaskStore

Thread → ThreadStore

Trace → TraceEngine

Output
System initialized with root context
🔹 Step 2: CEO Planning Phase
Flow
CEO analyzes task → breaks into subtasks
Actions

Create CEO Thread

Define:

subtasks

required capabilities

team structure

Decision Point
Are required agents available?
🔹 Step 3: Agent Discovery / Hiring
Case A: Agents Available
Directory खोजता है suitable agents
Case B: Missing Capability
CEO → AgentFactory → HireAgent()
Hiring Flow
Requirement → Template → Generate → Deploy → Register
Output
All required agents available
🔹 Step 4: Team Formation
CEO Creates Teams
Team Alpha → Manager + Workers  
Team Beta  → Manager + Workers
Actions

Assign:

Manager

Workers

Create Manager Threads

Link to Task

🔹 Step 5: Manager Task Distribution
Flow
Manager → Workers (via A2A)
Actions

Create Worker Threads

Send execution command

send({
  To: worker,
  TaskID: taskID,
  ThreadID: workerThreadID,
  Name: "execute_task"
})
🔹 Step 6: Worker Execution + Self-Critique
Flow
Worker executes → reviews → improves → finalizes
Internal Loop (MANDATORY)
1. Generate output  
2. Self-review  
3. Improve  
4. Repeat (2–3 times minimum)  
After Finalization

Update TaskStore

Send result to Manager

🔹 Step 7: Manager Validation
Flow
Manager reviews worker output
Decision
✅ If VALID
Forward to Testing
❌ If INVALID
Reject → send back to Worker
Feedback Logging

Add Feedback entry

Attach ThreadID

🔹 Step 8: Testing Phase (Final Gate)
Flow
Manager → Testing Agent
Testing Actions

Validate correctness

Validate requirements alignment

Detect bugs

Decision
✅ PASS
Task proceeds to completion
❌ FAIL
Feedback generated → back to Manager/Worker
🔹 Step 9: Feedback Loop
Trigger Conditions

Manager rejection

Testing failure

Client dissatisfaction

Actions
Feedback stored → Feedback Team analyzes
Output

Recommendations:

improve agent

replace agent

hire new agent

🔹 Step 10: CEO Intervention (ANYTIME)

CEO can intervene at ANY stage:

Examples
1. Check Status
GetTask(taskID)
2. Override Execution
send({
  To: agent,
  Name: "override_instruction"
})
3. Replace Agent
Worker → replaced with new worker
4. Terminate Task
Stop execution completely
🔹 Step 11: Task Completion
Conditions

All subtasks completed

Testing passed

No open feedback

Actions
Update task status → completed
Close threads
Finalize trace
🧵 5.4 Thread Lifecycle
Lifecycle
Created → Running → Completed / Failed
Rules

Every agent action → new thread or subthread

Parent-child must be maintained

🔄 5.5 Retry & Iteration Flow
When triggered:

Worker failure

Manager rejection

Testing failure

Flow
Reject → Feedback → Fix → Re-run
⚡ 5.6 Parallel Execution Model
Behavior
Multiple workers execute simultaneously
Rules

No shared state

TaskStore used for sync

Independent threads

📈 5.7 Scaling Behavior in Runtime
Scenario
100 worker instances available
Behavior

Any worker can pick any task

Load distributed automatically

Requirement
Idempotent execution required
🚨 5.8 Failure Handling Flow
Types of Failures
1. Agent Failure
Reassign task to another instance
2. Bad Output
Reject → Feedback → Retry
3. System Failure
Retry via middleware
🔐 5.9 Guarantees from Lifecycle
✅ Traceability

Every step logged

✅ Fault Tolerance

Failures handled gracefully

✅ Scalability

Parallel execution supported

✅ Quality Assurance

Multi-layer validation

⚠️ 5.10 Common Flow Mistakes (Avoid)

❌ Skipping thread creation
❌ Not updating TaskStore
❌ Workers bypassing managers
❌ Testing skipped
❌ Feedback ignored

🎯 5.11 Final Execution Philosophy
Plan → Execute → Validate → Test → Improve → Repeat
