TECH PRD — Section 6: Agent Communication Protocol (A2A Spec)
🧠 6.1 Purpose of This Section

This section defines:

How agents communicate, validate, route, and observe messages across the system

It ensures:

Reliable communication

Full traceability

Transport independence

Strict validation

🧱 6.2 Core Principles of A2A Communication
✅ Principle 1: Protocol-First Communication
All communication MUST use A2A messages
✅ Principle 2: Transport Agnostic

Same message works for:

in-process | HTTP | gRPC
✅ Principle 3: Context Propagation

Every message MUST carry:

TaskID + ThreadID + TraceID
✅ Principle 4: Idempotency
Repeated messages MUST NOT break system state
✅ Principle 5: Observability Built-in

Every message:

logged

traced

measurable

📡 6.3 A2A Message Contract (FINAL)
🧩 Message Structure
type A2AMessage struct {
    MessageID string

    From      string
    To        string

    Capability string // optional (dynamic routing)

    TaskID     string
    ThreadID   string
    TraceID    string

    Type       string // command | query | event
    Name       string

    Payload    interface{}

    Metadata   map[string]string

    Timestamp  time.Time
}
🧩 Response Structure
type A2AResponse struct {
    MessageID string

    Status    string // success | error

    Payload   interface{}
    Error     string

    Timestamp time.Time
}
⚠️ Mandatory Fields

Every message MUST include:

MessageID  
From  
(TaskID, ThreadID, TraceID)  
Type  
Name  
Timestamp  
🧭 6.4 Message Types
1. Command
"Do something"

Example:

execute_task
hire_agent
override_instruction
2. Query
"Give me information"

Example:

get_task_status
get_agent_metrics
3. Event
"Something happened"

Example:

task.updated
agent.hired
task.completed
🔀 6.5 Routing Mechanism
🧠 Routing Modes
1. Direct Routing
To: "manager-agent"
2. Capability-Based Routing (Recommended)
Capability: "write_blog"
🔍 Resolution Flow
1. Message received
2. If To exists → direct
3. Else → resolve via directory
4. Select best agent
5. Forward message
🧠 Load Balancing (Important for Scaling)

If multiple instances exist:

Pick instance using:
- round robin
- least busy
- best performance
🚚 6.6 Transport Layer Design
🔌 Supported Transports
1. In-Process Transport
Used when agents are in same runtime
agent.Handle(msg)
2. HTTP Transport (A2A Compatible)
Used for cross-service communication
POST /a2a/message
3. gRPC Transport (Optional)
High-performance distributed systems
🧠 Transport Selection Logic
func selectTransport(agent AgentProfile) Transport {
    if agent.Endpoints.InProc {
        return InProc
    }
    if agent.Endpoints.GRPC != "" {
        return GRPC
    }
    return HTTP
}
🧩 6.7 Middleware Stack (CRITICAL)

Every message passes through middleware:

Receive → Validate → Trace → Log → Retry → Route → Handle → Respond
🧱 Required Middleware
1. Validation Middleware

Check required fields

Reject invalid messages

2. Trace Middleware

Attach TraceID

Record TraceStep

3. Logging Middleware

Store message logs

Debug visibility

4. Retry Middleware

Retry failed messages

Handle transient errors

5. Timeout Middleware

Prevent stuck requests

6. Idempotency Middleware

Deduplicate messages

🔁 6.8 Retry & Failure Handling
Retry Strategy
Retry up to N times with exponential backoff
Failure Types
1. Network Failure

→ retry

2. Agent Busy

→ retry OR route to another instance

3. Logical Error

→ return error → handled upstream

🔐 6.9 Idempotency Design
Problem

Duplicate messages can occur.

Solution

Each message must have:

MessageID (unique)
Store processed messages:
if already processed → ignore
📊 6.10 Observability in Communication

Every message must:

1. Create Trace Step
From → To → Action
2. Log Message

request

response

errors

3. Metrics

Track:

latency

success rate

retries

🔄 6.11 End-to-End Message Flow
1. Agent sends message

2. Middleware validates

3. Directory resolves target

4. Transport selected

5. Message delivered

6. Target agent processes

7. Response returned

8. Trace updated
⚠️ 6.12 Common Implementation Mistakes (Avoid)

❌ Missing TraceID
❌ Skipping middleware
❌ Hardcoding agent IDs
❌ No retry logic
❌ Not handling duplicate messages

🎯 6.13 Final Communication Philosophy
Reliable → Traceable → Scalable → Decoupled
📌 End of Section 6

TECH PRD — Section 7: Scalability, Deployment & Infrastructure Design
🧠 7.1 Purpose of This Section

This section defines:

How the system is deployed, scaled, and operated in real-world environments

It ensures:

Massive horizontal scalability

Fault tolerance

Efficient resource usage

Clear deployment model

🧱 7.2 Deployment Philosophy
🔑 Core Principle
Scale horizontally, not vertically
🔑 System Behavior

Agents are stateless

Work is distributed

State is centralized (DB / store)

🔑 Outcome
Any agent instance can process any task
🏗️ 7.3 Deployment Architecture (Kubernetes Recommended)
🧩 High-Level Infra
                 ┌──────────────────────┐
                 │       CLIENT         │
                 └─────────┬────────────┘
                           │
                  ┌────────▼────────┐
                  │   API Gateway   │
                  └────────┬────────┘
                           │
        ┌──────────────────┼──────────────────┐
        │                  │                  │
 ┌──────▼──────┐   ┌──────▼──────┐   ┌──────▼──────┐
 │ CEO PODS    │   │ MANAGER PODS│   │ WORKER PODS │
 └──────┬──────┘   └──────┬──────┘   └──────┬──────┘
        │                 │                 │
        └──────────┬──────┴──────┬──────────┘
                   │             │
        ┌──────────▼──────┐ ┌────▼──────────┐
        │ TASK STORE (DB) │ │ MESSAGE LAYER │
        └─────────────────┘ └───────────────┘
⚙️ 7.4 Core Infrastructure Components
1. API Gateway
Responsibilities:

Entry point for client requests

Authentication

Rate limiting

Request routing

2. Agent Services

Each agent type runs as:

Independent scalable service
3. Task Store (Database)

Recommended:

PostgreSQL (primary)

Redis (optional caching)

4. Message Layer (A2A Transport)

HTTP / gRPC endpoints

Internal routing

📈 7.5 Horizontal Scaling Strategy
🔥 Key Idea
Scale by adding more agent instances (pods)
🧩 Example
100 worker agents → 500 worker pods
🧠 Behavior

All workers identical

Tasks distributed dynamically

No central bottleneck

⚙️ Scaling Rules
1. Workers Scale Most
Workers = highest scaling factor
2. Managers Moderate Scale
Managers = fewer but scalable
3. CEO Minimal Scale
CEO = 1–N (low scaling)
🔄 7.6 Task Distribution Model
🧠 Pull-Based Model (Recommended)

Instead of pushing tasks:

Workers PULL tasks from TaskStore
Flow
1. Worker requests task
2. TaskStore assigns available task
3. Worker locks task
4. Executes
🔐 Task Locking
Prevent multiple workers doing same work
Example
Lock(taskID, workerID)
⚡ 7.7 Load Balancing Strategy
🧠 Levels of Load Balancing
1. Infra Level (Kubernetes)

Service-based routing

Round-robin

2. Application Level

Agent Directory decides:

Best instance based on:
- load
- latency
- success rate
🧬 7.8 Agent Instance Management
🧩 Identity Model
Agent ID     → logical identity
Instance ID  → physical instance
🧠 Example
blog-agent
  ├── instance-1 (pod A)
  ├── instance-2 (pod B)
📊 Health Tracking

Each instance must:

heartbeat periodically

update status

🔍 7.9 Service Discovery
🧠 Mechanism

Agent Directory acts as:

Service Registry
Responsibilities:

Track instances

Provide endpoints

Enable routing

🚨 7.10 Fault Tolerance Design
🔥 Failure Types
1. Agent Crash
Reassign task to another instance
2. Network Failure
Retry via middleware
3. Partial Execution
Resume from TaskStore state
🔁 Retry Strategy
Exponential backoff
Max retry limit
Fallback to other instance
📦 7.11 Stateless Execution Requirement
🔑 Rule
Agents must be stateless
Why?

Enables scaling

Prevents inconsistency

Simplifies recovery

Implementation

Read from TaskStore

Process

Write back

🧠 7.12 Data Layer Design
Primary DB

PostgreSQL

Optional Layers

Redis → caching

Queue (NATS/Kafka) → async events

🔄 7.13 Event-Driven Extensions (Optional but Recommended)
Add Pub/Sub System
task.updated  
agent.hired  
task.completed  
Benefits

real-time updates

decoupling

scalability

🔐 7.14 Security & Isolation
Basic Requirements

Auth between agents

Request validation

Rate limiting

Future Enhancements

mTLS

service mesh

📊 7.15 Monitoring & Metrics
Track:

task throughput

agent success rate

latency

failure rate

Tools (suggested):

Prometheus

Grafana

⚠️ 7.16 Common Infrastructure Mistakes

❌ Stateful agents
❌ No task locking
❌ Single point of failure
❌ Ignoring retries
❌ Over-centralizing CEO

🎯 7.17 Final Infrastructure Philosophy
Distributed → Stateless → Scalable → Fault-Tolerant → Observable
📌 End of Section 7

TECH PRD — Section 8: Testing, Validation & Quality Assurance System
🧠 8.1 Purpose of This Section

This section defines:

How the system guarantees correctness, alignment, and production-grade output

It ensures:

No incorrect output reaches client

Multi-layer validation is enforced

Quality is measurable and improvable

🧱 8.2 Quality Philosophy
🔥 Core Principle
"Nothing is trusted until it is tested"
🧠 Multi-Layer Validation Model
Worker (self-check)
   ↓
Manager (strict validation)
   ↓
Testing Team (final authority)
   ↓
Feedback (continuous improvement)
🧩 8.3 Validation Layers (DETAILED)
🔹 Layer 1: Worker Self-Validation
Purpose

Catch errors before submission

Mandatory Process
Generate → Review → Improve → Review → Finalize
Minimum Requirements

At least 2–3 internal review passes

Check:

correctness

completeness

edge cases

requirement alignment

Output Format
type WorkerOutput struct {
    Result      interface{}
    Confidence  float64
    SelfReview  []string
}
⚠️ Rules

❗ Low confidence output MUST NOT be submitted
❗ Worker must reject its own weak output

🔹 Layer 2: Manager Validation
Purpose

Ensure:

Output matches business requirements EXACTLY
Validation Checklist

Manager must verify:

Requirement alignment

Completeness

Logical correctness

No ambiguity

Manager Decision
type ManagerDecision struct {
    Status string // APPROVED | REJECTED
    Issues []string
}
⚠️ Manager Strict Rules

❗ Reject if ANY issue exists
❗ No partial approvals
❗ No "almost correct"

🔹 Layer 3: Testing Team (FINAL GATE)
Purpose

Independent validation before final output

Testing Scope
1. Functional Testing

Does it work correctly?

2. Requirement Testing

Does it match client intent?

3. Edge Case Testing

Handles unusual inputs?

4. Consistency Testing

Matches system standards?

Output
type TestResult struct {
    Status string // PASS | FAIL
    Issues []string
}
⚠️ Testing Rules

❗ Testing team is completely independent
❗ Must FAIL if ANY issue exists
❗ Cannot trust Manager blindly

📊 8.4 Quality Scoring System
🧠 Purpose

Measure and improve agent performance

🧩 Score Model
type QualityScore struct {
    AgentID string

    Accuracy     float64
    Completeness float64
    Reliability  float64

    OverallScore float64
}
📈 Usage

Rank agents

Select best agents

Trigger improvements

🔁 8.5 Iteration & Retry Flow
Trigger Conditions

Manager rejection

Testing failure

Client dissatisfaction

Flow
Reject → Feedback → Improve → Re-execute
📉 8.6 Failure Classification
Types of Failures
1. Logical Error
Incorrect reasoning
2. Requirement Misalignment
Did not follow instructions
3. Incomplete Work
Missing parts
4. Low Quality
Poor clarity or depth
🧠 8.7 Automated Validation Rules
Examples
Rule 1: Required Fields
Reject if output missing required data
Rule 2: Schema Validation
Output must match expected schema
Rule 3: Confidence Threshold
Reject if confidence < threshold
🔄 8.8 Continuous Quality Improvement
Feedback Loop
Failure → Feedback → Analysis → Improvement
Improvements Trigger

Retrain agent

Replace agent

Hire new agent

🧪 8.9 Testing Strategies
1. Unit Testing (Agent Level)

Test individual agent behavior

2. Integration Testing

Agent-to-agent interaction

3. End-to-End Testing

Full task execution

📦 8.10 Test Data Management
Requirements

Realistic scenarios

Edge cases

Failure cases

🔐 8.11 Quality Guarantees
✅ No unvalidated output
✅ Multi-layer validation enforced
✅ Continuous improvement
✅ Measurable quality
⚠️ 8.12 Common Quality Failures (Avoid)

❌ Workers skipping self-review
❌ Managers being lenient
❌ Testing bypassed
❌ No feedback loop
❌ No quality metrics

🎯 8.13 Final Quality Philosophy
Self-check → Strict validation → Ruthless testing → Continuous improvement
📌 End of Section 8

TECH PRD — Section 9: Observability, Monitoring & Debugging System
🧠 9.1 Purpose of This Section

This section defines:

How the system exposes visibility into execution, performance, failures, and behavior

It ensures:

Full transparency of agent actions

Fast debugging and root cause analysis

Real-time monitoring of system health

Visual understanding of execution flow

🧱 9.2 Observability Philosophy
🔥 Core Principle
"If you can't see it, you can't trust or debug it"
🧠 Observability Pillars
1. Tracing     → What happened?
2. Logging     → What details?
3. Metrics     → How well?
4. Visualization → How does it all connect?
🧵 9.3 Trace System (Execution Visibility Core)
🔥 What It Is

Tracks:

End-to-end execution of a task across all agents
🧩 Trace Model
type Trace struct {
    TraceID   string
    TaskID    string
    StartedAt time.Time
}
🧩 Trace Step
type TraceStep struct {
    StepID    string
    TraceID   string

    From      string
    To        string

    Action    string
    ThreadID  string

    Timestamp time.Time
}
🧠 What It Captures

Agent interactions

Decisions made

Execution flow

Failures

🌳 9.4 Thread Graph Visualization
🔥 What It Is

A hierarchical view of execution

Structure
Client Thread
  └── CEO Thread
        └── Manager Thread (Team A)
              ├── Worker Thread (A1)
              ├── Worker Thread (A2)
        └── Testing Thread
🧠 UI Capabilities (REQUIRED)
1. Expandable Graph View

Click → expand subthreads

2. Agent/Team Filtering
Show only Manager / Worker / Team Alpha
3. Status Highlighting

Green → success

Red → failure

Yellow → in progress

4. Timeline View

Replay execution step-by-step

📝 9.5 Logging System
🔥 Purpose

Capture detailed system activity

🧩 Log Structure
type LogEntry struct {
    LogID     string

    TaskID    string
    ThreadID  string
    TraceID   string

    AgentID   string

    Level     string // INFO, WARN, ERROR

    Message   string
    Metadata  map[string]interface{}

    Timestamp time.Time
}
🧠 Logging Requirements
Must Log:

Incoming messages

Outgoing messages

Decisions

Errors

Retries

⚠️ Rules

❗ No silent failures
❗ All errors MUST be logged
❗ Logs MUST be structured (no plain text only)

📊 9.6 Metrics System
🔥 Purpose

Measure system performance

🧩 Metrics Categories
1. Task Metrics

task completion time

success rate

retry count

2. Agent Metrics

success rate

error rate

latency

3. System Metrics

throughput

active tasks

resource usage

🧠 Example Metrics
worker_success_rate = 0.94
avg_task_latency = 120ms
task_failure_rate = 0.03
🔍 9.7 Debugging System
🔥 Goal

Enable developers to:

Quickly identify WHAT failed, WHERE, and WHY
🧩 Debug Capabilities
1. Trace Replay
Replay entire execution flow step-by-step
2. Thread Inspection

inspect any thread

see inputs/outputs

3. Message Inspection

view A2A messages

payload + response

4. Failure Drill-Down
Task → Thread → Agent → Error
🚨 9.8 Alerting System
🔥 Purpose

Detect issues proactively

🚨 Alert Types
1. High Failure Rate
If agent failure > threshold
2. Latency Spike
If response time increases
3. Task Stuck
If task not progressing
🧠 Actions

notify CEO agent

trigger auto-scaling

trigger fallback

🔄 9.9 Observability Flow
Message → Middleware → TraceStep
                ↓
             Logging
                ↓
             Metrics
                ↓
          Visualization UI
🧠 9.10 Integration with System Components
Component	Observability Role
A2A	logs + trace
TaskStore	state visibility
ThreadStore	graph
Feedback	failure insight
AgentDirectory	performance
🔐 9.11 Guarantees
✅ Full Traceability

Every action can be traced

✅ Debuggability

Issues can be diagnosed quickly

✅ Transparency

System behavior is visible

⚠️ 9.12 Common Observability Mistakes

❌ Missing TraceID
❌ Logging unstructured data
❌ No thread graph
❌ Ignoring metrics
❌ No alerting

🎯 9.13 Final Observability Philosophy
Trace everything → Log everything → Measure everything → Visualize everything
📌 End of Section 9

TECH PRD — Section 10: Security, Governance Policies & Future Enhancements
🧠 10.1 Purpose of This Section

This section defines:

How the system is secured, governed, controlled, and evolved over time

It ensures:

Safe and controlled agent behavior

Proper access control

Protection against misuse or failure

Clear roadmap for future growth

🔐 10.2 Security Philosophy
🔥 Core Principle
"Zero Trust System — verify everything, trust nothing"
🧠 Security Layers
1. Identity & Authentication
2. Authorization & Access Control
3. Communication Security
4. Data Protection
5. Runtime Safety
🔑 10.3 Identity & Authentication
🧩 Agent Identity

Each agent must have:

AgentID (logical)
InstanceID (physical)
🔐 Authentication Mechanism
Minimum (v1)

API keys / tokens between services

Recommended (v2+)

mTLS (mutual TLS)

service identity (SPIFFE/SPIRE style)

⚠️ Rules

❗ Every request must be authenticated
❗ No anonymous agent communication

🛂 10.4 Authorization & Access Control
🧠 Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
Roles
CEO → full access  
Manager → team-level access  
Worker → task-level access  
Tester → validation-only access  
Feedback → analysis-only access  
🔐 Access Rules
CEO

Can access everything

Can override any agent

Manager

Access only assigned tasks & team

Worker

Access only assigned thread/task

Testing

Access outputs only

⚠️ Enforcement

All access must be validated at:

A2A middleware layer
🔒 10.5 Communication Security
🔐 Requirements
1. Encryption
All communication must be encrypted (HTTPS / TLS)
2. Message Integrity

Prevent tampering

Validate message structure

3. Replay Protection

Use MessageID

Reject duplicates

🛡️ 10.6 Data Protection
🔐 Sensitive Data Handling
Rules

No sensitive data in logs

Mask confidential fields

Encrypt stored secrets

🧠 Storage Security

DB access control

encrypted storage (at rest)

⚙️ 10.7 Runtime Safety Controls
🚨 Problem

Agents can:

behave incorrectly

produce bad outputs

loop infinitely

🔧 Solutions
1. Execution Limits
Max retries  
Max execution time  
2. Rate Limiting

Prevent:

Agent overload / spam
3. Kill Switch (CEO Control)

CEO can:

Terminate task  
Stop agent  
Override behavior  
⚖️ 10.8 Governance Policies
🧠 Policy Types
1. Quality Policy

No untested output

Strict validation enforced

2. Hiring Policy

CEO must ensure:

New agents meet quality standards
3. Replacement Policy

Replace agent if:

repeated failures

low performance

4. Feedback Policy
All failures MUST generate feedback
5. Escalation Policy
Worker → Manager → CEO → Client
